  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national money laundering laws in several key ways:\n\n1. Global Standards and Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations conventions against transnational organized crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards for preventing money laundering\n\n2. Legal Cooperation Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border investigations and prosecutions\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance\n- Countries implement international standards into domestic legislation\n- Banks and financial institutions required to follow Know Your Customer (KYC) rules\n- Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions\n- International sanctions enforcement\n\n4. Enforcement Coordination\n- Joint investigative teams\n- Interpol and international law enforcement collaboration\n- Seizure and asset recovery mechanisms\n- Tracking and disrupting complex financial crimes\n\n5. Technological Challenges\n- Addressing cryptocurrency and digital financial systems\n- Developing consistent regulatory approaches\n- Managing cross-border digital financial transactions\n\n6. Jurisdictional Considerations\n- Resolving conflicts between different legal systems\n- Addressing variations in legal definitions\n- Ensuring consistent implementation of anti-money laundering protocols\n\nThese intersections create complex but increasingly sophisticated global anti-money laundering frameworks.",
